tweet: In addition: an additional $1 million has been granted to the Coalition on Homelessness and Housing in Ohio to help Ohio's homeless shelters purchase needed cleaning supplies and also provide homelessness prevention and housing services.

tweet: Of this, $1 million is earmarked for the Agricultural Clearance Program, where the Ohio Association of Foodbanks will purchase Ohio-made commodities, such as milk, to distribute to foodbanks across the state.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: On Friday, Governor DeWine signed an Executive Order to provide nearly $5 million in emergency funding from the Temporary Assistance to Needy Families (TANF) block grant to support Ohio’s 12 Feeding America foodbanks and the statewide hunger relief network.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: ....a bill with the person’s name and Ohio address on it, or a letter from an employer placing the person in Ohio as an essential employee.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Sale of liquor to a person with a valid non-Ohio photo ID may only occur with additional information showing that the person resides in Ohio, including mail with the person’s name and Ohio address on it....

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: From this point forward, for an individual to purchase liquor in Ashtabula, Trumbull, Mahoning, Columbiana, Jefferson, and Belmont Counties, that person will need to present a valid #Ohio photo ID or a valid military photo ID for a person in active duty status

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This is necessary because of repeated instances of persons from Pennsylvania coming into these counties for the sole or main purpose of purchasing liquor. Any other time, we'd love to have visitors from PA, but right now this creates an unacceptable public health issue.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
Liquor Update: In compliance with @OHdeptofhealth orders designed to prevent the further spread of #COVID19, the in-person sale of liquor in these counties will be restricted only to Ohioans:

➡️ Ashtabula
➡️ Trumbull
➡️ Mahoning
➡️ Columbiana
➡️ Jefferson
➡️ Belmont

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Further, we will be providing a list of long-term care facilities where an associated individual has tested positive on our website.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: @OHdeptofhealth  had been strongly encouraging facilities to notify families before this.  However, this is now required.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Nursing Homes: I’ve asked Dr. Acton to issue an order that will require long-term care facilities to notify residents and families within 24 hours of a resident or staff member becoming infected.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Additionally, sadly, an inmate housed at Pickaway Correctional has died. That inmate had a long-term chronic illness and was tested for #COVID19 before his death. The test results returned positive today. This the 1st death of a state inmate who has tested positive for the virus.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Update on prisons: The @OHNationalGuard will begin providing assistance to the medical staff at Pickaway Correctional Institution. There are a number of medical staff out sick due to #COVID19 - they will provide triage support, taking temps, and helping with non-COVID19 cases.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Additionally, companies should ask for a letter of authorization from the FDA on their anti-body test kit, which is proof they have been approved. The website and list of new vendors is updated daily.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Many of these testing companies are legitimately in the queue at the FDA for approval, which will help expand the use.  However, I would recommend that you only use companies that are listed on the FDA website.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: However, I wanted to caution all companies looking at this option to ensure they are only buying FDA Emergency Use Authorization (EUA) approved anti-body tests.  Without this FDA Emergency Use Authorization approval, there is no way to know if the tests are valid.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have heard that some companies in Ohio are purchasing rapid anti-body tests to begin testing their staff and, in some cases, their customers.  Anti-body testing is one piece to the puzzle on determining when employees can return to work.

tweet: The bottom line is that patients should talk to their doctors.  If a physician’s clinical judgment about a procedure is essential, then it should continue.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
Criteria for essential:
Threat to the patient’s life if the surgery or procedure is not performed; Threat of permanent dysfunction of an extremity or organ system if not performed; Risk of progression or worsening of a condition or disease; Risk of rapidly worsening symptoms.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The managed care plans have already lifted prior authorizations for all but a few services. This took effect on 3-27. Physicians and other providers, without prior authorization by a managed care plan, are using clinical judgment to determine if something is a medical necessity.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
oMember co-pays will be waived. This is for all prescriptions.
o90-day supplies on maintenance medications will be authorized.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
oThe threshold for refills on certain prescriptions will be relaxed.
oPharmacists who dispense emergency refills without a prescription will be reimbursed.
oPharmacies that dispense over-the-counter medications without a prescription will be reimbursed.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
Here is an overview of these changes.

Medicaid has eased several pharmacy benefit restrictions. 
oPrior authorizations will be by-passed for new prescriptions.
oMembers will receive pharmacy benefits regardless of in-network or out-of-network provider status.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: If you look at the hospitalizations, they're going up every day. We compare it every day against the five-day average and we are seeing that those admissions are still going up. But the things we are seeing are still very encouraging. We're optimistic.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are working just as hard on how we come back from this as we were when we focused on the #StayHomeOhio order. The only way we are going to be able to move forward is if we all continue to do what we're doing.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We're working on a very sophisticated plan. We're not going to lay that out today, it is still a work in progress, but it is coming along. Soon we will outline it out for you.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Where do we go from here? @LtGovHusted, @DrAmyActon, and our team who you never see - we're all working day and night. We're all working very, very hard to set a path out about how we come out of this and get back to work. How we get back to living our lives.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have to continue doing what we're doing. If we do that - the new projections will continue. If we let up, they will not continue.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The track we go on is based on what we all do. We've hit a home run. We've done a great job, but it is not time to celebrate. The game is not over. The optimistic scenarios are based on a belief that we will continue #SocialDistancing at the same level.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: It's about what YOU do and don't do. You've all been doing a bang-up job. The initial modelers - they didn't think Ohio was going to do as good a job as we did.  We did a lot better. That's one reason why the model has changed so much. pic.twitter.com/jb7VG0g7fH

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: But overall, things are turning out - so far - better for #Ohio. The reason the models are changing is because of each and every one of you. It's what YOU have done. You've made a huge difference. I've said before - it's not about the orders we issue.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have tried every day to tell you what we know when we know it. We've had some questions about the curve and how much it was flattened. We're seeing some of these estimates changing. You're seeing the estimates getting better, but we also have Ohioans dying every day. pic.twitter.com/lXil8XWJoJ

name: Governor Mike DeWine

Approximately $1.4 billion will go to private employers; Approximately $200 million will go to local government taxing districts (counties, cities, schools, etc.)

Checks will start going out later this month.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Even with the downturn in the market, @OhioBWC is able to provide this important dividend to employers while maintaining funds to take care of injured workers for years to come.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: As in previous years, the dividend is possible due to strong investment returns on employer premiums, a declining number of claims each year, and prudent fiscal management. It’s also due to employers who work hard to improve workplace safety and reduce injury claims.

tweet: Any amounts exceeding outstanding balances will be sent to the employer.  For those employers, it means one less bill to worry about.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: They are making sure that Ohioans will be able to receive care when they need it.  I want to thank all of the members of the @OHNationalGuard for also helping to collect, take inventory, store, and package personal protection equipment for redistribution across the state.

tweet: I also want to take a moment to thank our children services workers. They are going above and beyond to ensure our children are safe during this pandemic. What you are doing every day is vital, and we are grateful for your efforts to protect Ohio children.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Ohioans - we have a couple hard weeks ahead of us. The sacrifices we are making are painful sacrifices. But if we let up, we will begin to look like the yellow curve. pic.twitter.com/xOFk9hDxmy

tweet: We're starting to see hotspots. Near Detroit, near nursing homes, near a prison. That why we're building up our healthcare system. pic.twitter.com/rham4ndo98

tweet: HOWEVER, if we let up, cases will go up. The second we let our foot off the gas, it can pick up again.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: It's important to think in worst-case scenarios so that we can aim well and work to prevent it. We have to continue to think about worst-case scenarios.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We look at the worst-case scenarios and other modeling showing better outcomes. This all points us in a general direction of decision making - maybe when the peak will be. Maybe when we'll need more ventilators.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Let's talk about modeling. There is a lot being said about modeling - but it is not a science that predicts the outcome. Our actions predict the outcome. Modeling is like a weather forecast - even forecasts use many models.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Overall, these are all tough decisions. We are trying to take a measured and reasonable approach that protects the public and tries to minimize the spread.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: If the parole board recommends that a sentence be commuted, they can also recommend additional conditions on the release of the inmate. As governor, I can accept and/or add conditions. If the conditions are violated, they'll serve their remaining sentence.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: After the parole board makes a recommendation on these 26 cases, I’ll act quickly to make my decision in respect to each case.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: In these 26 cases, it is a statutory requirement that the parole board to consider and make a recommendation on each of these cases. In those cases where there are specific victims, those victims will receive notice and have the opportunity for their voices to be heard.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are asking judges and prosecutors associated with these cases to waive the 60 days notice so that they can take these cases directly to the parole board. The parole board is prepared to meet start meeting on Friday to address these matters.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Because of these individuals’ medical vulnerability, the fact that some would not qualify for judicial release and the need to consider these cases quickly, I'm taking the following action.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: As I explained yesterday, under the normal procedure I cannot quickly grant a commutation – we must give prosecutors, judges, and victims notice of at least 60 days – and that’s after all the appropriate paperwork has been filed.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We also took out habitual offenders – those with 2 or more prior convictions. This left us with 26 inmates statewide.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
We also screened out those who have: 
•Been denied judicial release in the past. 
•Have had prior incarcerations in Ohio
•Are not inter-state offenders, 
•Have warrants or detainers, and 
•Those who have has serious prison rule violations in the last several years.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
•sex offenses, 
•homicide-related offenses, 
•kidnapping, 
•abduction, 
•ethnic intimidation, 
•making terroristic threats, and
•domestic violence.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We also looked for those who've served more than 50% of their sentence. Then we started screening out those convicted of charges such as:

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: There is another, much smaller, group of inmates who we believe should also be considered for release. These are inmates who are 60 years or older and have 1 or more chronic health condition that makes them more vulnerable to #COVID19.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Again - these are individuals are already approaching the end of their sentences and releasing them slightly earlier than planned will create more social distancing for those we must keep in custody. I encourage the CIIC to give this issue their immediate attention.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: These inmates are all in our minimum-security prisons. Prisoners in these facilities live in “open bays” w/ 80 to 300 people in a large open room. They sleep in bunks with three feet or less between them. Because of this set-up there is potential for the fast spread of #COVID19.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: That left us with 141 inmates who qualify for emergency release under Ohio’s Overcrowding Emergency statute and have a release date on or before July 13, 2020.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
We also screened out those who:
•Have been denied judicial release in the past. 
•Have prior incarcerations in Ohio
•Are inter-state offenders, 
•Have warrants or detainers, and 
•Those who have serious prison rule violations in the last 5 years.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
•sex offenses, 
•homicide-related offenses, 
•kidnapping, 
•abduction, 
•ethnic intimidation, 
•making terroristic threats, and
•domestic violence.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: To be clear, we’re not asking that everyone who is scheduled to be released within 90 days be released early. We narrowed down the list by first looking at those who are set to be released within 90 days and then eliminated those convicted of serious charges such as:

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: To help relieve this situation, we believe that there are specific inmates who could qualify for release who are already scheduled for release within the next 90 days.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are in an emergency that makes the situation more urgent. We are in unprecedented times, which is why I’m announcing today that we are moving forward with this process and are notifying the CIIC of overcrowding in our prisons.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: In Ohio law, there is a longstanding statute (ORC 2967.18) that allows the director of @DRCOhio to alert the Correctional Institution Inspection Committee of an overcrowding emergency and recommend that certain inmates be released to make more room.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The murderers, the sexual predators we have absolutely no intention of releasing them back into society. To protect the public, we must be smart and targeted about who we recommend for release.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Finding inmates to release from prisons to create more room for social distancing isn’t easy. We have around 49,000 people in our prisons today, and they’re there for a reason.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Last week we asked judges to consider the early release of 38 select offenders 23 pregnant or post-partum women and 15 inmates ages 60 and up who are already approaching release within 120 days. Since then, my team has continued to carefully analyze our prison population.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Recently, @DRCOhio's intake went down by around 20%. That has started to reduce our population in the prisons. I want to thank those at the local level who have been involved in that.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We must do all we can to protect prison staff. They can’t work from home. We need them, we appreciate them, and we must give them the safest work environment we can. We also must protect inmates. And we must protect the public from those who may cause them harm.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Prisons pose a unique issue in this pandemic. Social distancing in the general population is helping us #FlattenTheCurve – but for prison inmates and staff, #socialdistancing becomes much more challenging. pic.twitter.com/chpVZUskQe

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are trying to pull people together in communities to make sure the hospitals and nursing home/other congregate settings are talking with each other. For example, we want nursing homes to know exactly to call if someone develops symptoms. This is very important to us.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We continue working on how our seniors and people in our nursing homes and those in our developmental disabilities community are going to get the best care possible in an organized way. pic.twitter.com/MzRvao2zCs

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Under the rule, patrons can purchase two, prepackaged drinks per meal.  All drinks must be closed and remain closed during transport as per open container law.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Today, the Ohio Liquor Control Commission passed an emergency rule to allow establishments with an existing on-premises liquor permit to sell and deliver alcohol, including high-proof liquor in limited quantity, for off-premises consumption

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: All SNAP-eligible households will soon be belt o pick up a pre-packaged box of food at their local foodbank.  Ohio obtained federal approval to waive administrative verifications normally required at food banks, to streamline the process and limit person-to-person contact.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Our Ohio Department of Job and Family Services (ODJFS) announced today that those who did not already receive the maximum month allotment for their household size in March will be issued an additional payment beginning this week.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Ohioans enrolled in the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) will soon receive additional support to help them during the pandemic.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: In a time when libraries are closed, librarians continue to work. @statelibohio has compiled a massive calendar of library events across the state.  Visit:  http://library.ohio.gov/public-covid19-programs …. pic.twitter.com/2kcaJgKmyk

tweet: From @Akron_Police: "We came to work for you, please stay home for us." #StayHomeOhio #InThisTogetherOhio https://twitter.com/Akron_Police/status/1247505606925111296 …

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: A nice shoutout to #Ohio's frontline healthcare providers and first responders from Cub Scouts in Wintersville. #InThisTogetherOhio #StayHomeOhio https://twitter.com/moss_michelle/status/1246770932825436160 …

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: Double down on your commitment, Ohio. Let's fight this together. We do not want to be passive and let this virus own us. We need to own everything that is in our control. #InThisTogetherOhio #StayHomeOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: I don't think this is our peak week. I think our peak will be further out. But, what we're doing today is contributing to controlling the surge. Don't give up. Our ability to control this storm is in our hands. A huge part of it is what we are doing collectively.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Another thing: The number of prisoners coming in every week is going down, and that in itself is taking our population down. We want to give our prison officials more flexibility to move inmates around to better settings to reduce the spread of #COVID19.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We're going through a tough analysis of who we can release on different conditions. I don't have the power to release inmates quickly -- that's why this weekend we sent a first batch of inmates to judges to consider judicial release. We will be announcing more tomorrow.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I want to assure everyone who works in a prison, those who have family in prison, those who are in prison: We will do everything we can every day. This is something we will continue to battle, but @DRCOhio is doing a great deal to minimize inmate contact and stop #COVID19 spread.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: You all are moving mountains. You are saving lives. I get emotional when I talk about this. This is no small thing we are doing together. It's hard to shut down our lives the way we have. I know we will look back and know that we all saved each other in this state. pic.twitter.com/txHytUiRt4

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: We need to double the hospital capacity to handle the upcoming surge. But our social distancing has absolutely had an impact. This is going to be a hard week, and we have a couple hard weeks ahead. But we can't let up. The moment we let up it will all unravel. pic.twitter.com/JHdcF0C7Df

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: To those impacted by #COVID19, we are thinking of you and we care about you. We will do everything we can to give you the best care in #Ohio.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The second we can do widespread testing of the population, it's crucial to do that in a way that provides a good picture of race, ethnicity, the disabled, elderly, those dealing w/ life-threating illnesses, etc. -- we must not leave anyone behind. pic.twitter.com/HhlsqtryEV

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Cases/deaths by race and ethnicity in #Ohio. ⬇️ 25% of cases don't have race listed, and 39% don't list ethnicity. So, we know some people are opting out of providing that information. We are working to capture this data as best we can. We encourage people to fill in that data. pic.twitter.com/T9jh25oRKb

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We do have deaths as young as the 30-39 age range. We are seeing a higher number of female cases, but deaths are higher in males. pic.twitter.com/RAUWSVEI4e

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: @DrAmyActon: We will have new data coming soon that will give us new data from the hospitals. We do know that 303 of our cases that have been hospitalized and released, 25% of them have reached that period of recovery. pic.twitter.com/MT4xQ7Rqfm

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: Today's #COVID19 data dashboard for #Ohio. pic.twitter.com/QiHUzkhfTo

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: If you stick to what you're doing, there is reason to be optimistic. I think a lot of people are looking for optimism and you are providing it with your actions.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We're hopeful our destiny is changed by your actions. Don't let up, if you see this through, we are going to get out of this stronger.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: As you see, Ohioans, you're in gray. You've followed what we've all asked of each other. Data is thru the week of March 23. We hope the sacrifices you are making now will be in the modeling in the future. pic.twitter.com/bj8DwdWgFQ

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted - This map is a source of optimism. If you sacrifice now, you'll see the dividends later. Red shows people who are still traveling. On gray side, the more that people have been compliant with #SocialDistancing. pic.twitter.com/QscZ8Ni7C5

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
.@LtGovHusted: There are over 29,000 open jobs listed on  http://coronavirus.ohio.gov/jobsearch . 

These are great opportunities to pitch in and help the team of people trying to deliver the services we all need.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: Again, the new #StayHomeOhio order goes into effect at midnight tonight, including the dispute resolution commission. Find details at  http://coronavirus.ohio.gov/businesshelp . We will make the deliberation public and we expect to have a 24 hr turnaround time.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: For those coming into #Ohio after being out of state: To be clear, we're not talking about medical professionals, truckers, or those providing essential services. The order applies to those who vacationed elsewhere, went to a meeting in another state, etc.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are working with mobile food vendors to set up to provide truckers options for hot meals b/c the restaurant options are limited today.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
.@ODOT_Statewide Director Jack Marchbanks: 
The trucking industry is always a vital part of our economy. Their jobs are even more important now. We know this is a challenging time for this industry as it is for all of us. We're trying to make things easier for them. pic.twitter.com/cawkjdoeFN

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Overall we are doing pretty well. Ohioans are doing the right thing, and we can't let up. But we do have the concern that people coming in from other states will bring #COVID19 in with them.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Snowbirds coming back to #Ohio from places like Florida: Welcome back, we want you back -- but anyone coming back into Ohio (a resident or non-resident) must quarantine for 14 days.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We're not going to release anyone who is dangerous. We aren't releasing sex offenders, for example. We're going through the prisoners and taking a look at who might be getting close to release and who is in for a minor offense.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are testing those who have symptoms. Each employee is screened when they arrive and their temperature is taken. @DRCOhio has decreased programming with citizens from outside the facility. We will talk more tomorrow about more steps we will take re: releasing prisoners.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
Ohio Prisons:

5 inmates positive in Marion 
5 inmates positive in Pickaway Co 

Staff: 27 positive at 4 facilities, but most come from Marion.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Additionally, we’ve been receiving calls from family members of inmates at Elkton asking us to release the federal prisoners. I want to be clear that Ohio does not have the authority to release federal prisoners.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: In the meantime, I do, however, feel it necessary to make a plea to both the US Department of Justice and the Federal Bureau of Prisons to stop prisoner intake at this facility.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: As we've all said for weeks, we’re all in this together and providing state help for this federal prison is the right thing to do.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The @OHNationalGuard also stands ready to help with transporting the seriously ill patients to the hospital in the event of a surge. In addition to the staff, the guard will be bringing equipment and ambulances with them as well.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: These soldiers – who all work in the medical field - will have N-95 respirators for protection while they work to augment the current prison medical staff. They will treat those they can while triaging others with serious symptoms for hospital care.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: They’ll be there to assist with non-COVID cases, as well as with those who are showing symptoms of this highly contagious, deadly disease.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have an advance team from the guard there today, and we are prepared to send at least 26 guardsmen and women to the prison to help in the Elkton infirmary. This is a medical mission only. The guard members will not be armed and they will not be providing security.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: That’s why today I am announcing that I have authorized the Ohio National Guard to go into Elkton prison to assist. This is limited in duration and scope. Right now the plan is to go into the prison for 7-10 days until more federal assistance arrives.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: To be clear, this is not a state facility – But this prison is in #Ohio. Ohio citizens work there. Their families live here. When an inmate gets sick, they are transferred to local hospitals with Ohio doctors and nurses.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OhioAdjGen tells me that Elkton’s medical staffing right now is at 50%. And, for every 1 federal inmate at the hospital, they need 2 federal guards standing watch.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Update on federal prison in Ohio – Elkton Federal Correctional Institution in Columbiana County. This is a federal, not state facility. We know that 7 inmates have tested positive COVID-19 – but we also know that dozens more have shown symptoms – some very serious. 3 have died.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Everything you are doing in #Ohio is making a difference. We are all making a difference. We will do all we can to protect our protectors. We’ll leave no stone unturned to find what we need.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The @JobsOhio team provides input as part of the alliance and assists the state with rapid procurement requirements and identifying viable solutions.  I want to also thank former Governor @JohnKasich for creating JobsOhio - it is a tool we are using as we go through this crisis.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: A shoutout to @JobsOhio - shifted its business development effort and is now working to shore-up this critical supply chain. They know our manufacturing sector and what they can bring to the table.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have had at least 1400 Ohio manufacturing companies who have responded to our call to try and help in this crisis.  The Ohio Manufacturing Alliance reaches out to each company to find out where they fit into our strategy.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We appreciate all the medical professionals, companies, schools, colleges and universities, and individuals that have given PPE to our effort.  In times of crisis, as we have seen throughout our history, Ohioans act with great generosity, and so we #thankyou.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: And once we have our supplies, we’re going to use technology and innovation to identify ways to make our supplies last. A prime example is @Battelle is doing this right now, sterilizing masks for our healthcare workers. This is a great tool.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: As I’ve said before, we are too reliant on foreign marketplaces for our health care supplies. The efforts we’re making now in Ohio to address this crisis will help us today and I believe will strengthen our manufacturing sector in the future.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Procurement Update: As we continue to move through this crisis, we are working to ensure that our health care workers have the #PPE they need. If we can find it in the marketplace, we’re going to buy it. If we can’t buy it, we’re going to make it or repurpose it. pic.twitter.com/FMdB5XNe9h

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Health care regions in southern and southeastern Ohio have determined the existing hospital facilities in their areas will, with additional equipment, be able to handle the surge in patients without going to an off-site location.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Assessments of other sites will continue, as we look for additional space, should it be needed.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
1. Seagate Convention Center, Lucas Co
2. Case Western University’s Health Education Campus, Cuyahoga Co 
3. Dayton Convention Center, Montgomery Co
4. Covelli Convention Ctr, Mahoning Co
5. Duke Energy Convention Ctr, Hamilton Co
6. Greater Columbus Convention Ctr, Franklin Co

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: After visiting various locations and assessing for things, such as distance to an existing hospital, conditions safe for patients and health care professionals, and space to meet the region’s expected needs, the following sites have been selected:

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Representatives from health care systems, local governments, county emergency management agencies, state agencies, the @OHNationalGuard, among others, have teamed up in regions of the state to look at buildings that can support large numbers of patients.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Major hospitals and medical systems have put plans in place for expanding their capacity within their own facilities, or have collaborated on facilities. We have also been building a plan to expand health care at alternative sites.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Our hospital system has never seen a pandemic of this nature, so our response has to be unlike anything we’ve ever done before. Ohio has pulled resources and experts from multiple perspectives to combat this issue.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The # of customers allowed must also be listed. I'd like to congratulate those businesses that have already started doing this. Some stores are only doing one direction per aisle - this is a great idea that helps. Some retailers are also cleaning off carts/baskets btw customers.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Tonight at midnight, the requirements for the new #StayHomeOhio order begin. There are new requirements for retailers in this order, including determining a maximum number of customers allowed in the store to account for proper physical distancing. pic.twitter.com/IPjK3GRrSf

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Tomorrow is Palm Sunday.  In the Christian tradition, it marks the triumphal entrance of Jesus into the City of Jerusalem.  It begins Holy Week. It's going to be a different Palm Sunday b/c we can not gather together - it is much too dangerous.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This is the 27th straight day that we've had a news conference. The goal is to not be here again tomorrow unless there is breaking news.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The food is going to be there. The grocery stores are not running out of food. People need to have enough at home, but you don't need to hoard food. We're all #InThisTogetherOhio and we have to take care of each other and not become hoarders and take more than we need.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
Question: Will the #StayHomeOhio order go into the summer? 

Answer: We don't know. We will see where we go. You've heard Dr. Acton explain what the modelers are telling her, so we really don't know. pic.twitter.com/pyHAlofzP0

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: In some other countries, wearing a mask is considered cool and hip! I need you to wear both the cape and the mask now. I need you to understand that we are fighting for lives right now. Please don your cape, and when you're out and about, don your mask.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: It's not perfect - it's about 80% effective. But it can make a difference. Wash your hands before you use it so you don't contaminate the mask. I know #Ohio can lead the way in doing this. Tweet your pictures using #InThisTogetherOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: The culture change that is about to occur is in regard to this type of mask. We'll have information on  http://coronavirus.ohio.gov  on how to make these. This will help before we are symptomatic b/c it can make a difference in us spreading droplets to other people. pic.twitter.com/2DBxY28WXn

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have 15 people over the age of 60 and are approaching their release date that we believe could be released early. Again, these are not serious violent offenders.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We do have 23 women in our prison who are pregnant or have a child in prison. We will send a letter to the judge in their case to make a determination on if these women are appropriate to be released early.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are sending letters to judges in the state about 38 prisoners who might be able to be released early. These are not sex offenders, murderers, domestic abusers...we've screened out many people.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I felt it was important to look at our prison population. We have almost 49,000 prisoners. We've started to look at different prisons who it might make sense to send home early.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: But no system is perfect. We've seen what has been happening in other states.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Re Prisons: Our @DRCOhio team has done a great job. They've been working on their plan since February. Visitation has stopped, employees/contractors are screened, inmates coming in are screened, and we have a 5-week period where new inmates stay in reception. pic.twitter.com/nfL556B2Ph

tweet: Also - there is a shortage in the chemicals or reagents necessary to run the tests. Again, we have a group working on that to make sure these are available. The testing is complex and we are working to ramp up testing. That won't be set up overnight, but we are making progress.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: If you are frustrated - I'm frustrated too. This is not how we want to live. This is not what we signed up for, but it's where we are. My goal for all Ohioans is that we make it - that we get through this, live through it. What Ohioans are doing every day is saving lives. pic.twitter.com/mzpTZKKWxp

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: #SocialDistancing: I think 6 feet is a reasonable number to stick with, but I want you to use your judgment and don't forget the basics: wash your hands multiple times a day. Don't go out when you are sick.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: We know that most people who have #COVID19 are staying home. We will be able to start having data for those who were hospitalized and are recovering, but the real understanding will stay short for a while b/c of the lack of testing.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Some economists have said that in 1918, communities that did these tough things not only saved a lot of lives, but in the end, they were better off economically than the communities that let it spread, let people die, and let their healthcare system become overwhelmed.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This is very difficult. We would not make these decisions if it wasn't a matter of life and death. I know this is saving lives. We have to keep this monster down. It's not dead, it's very much alive. If we continue to #SocialDistance, we will lower the damage.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We all understand that this is tough. Congress has come forward with a comprehensive bill...it doesn't mean that it gets people back where they were, but it is helpful. I urge you to look at that bill to see what can be of direct help to you.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon has just signed the new #StayHomeOhio order. ⬇️ pic.twitter.com/Zpl7iN9pUF

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The sacrifices you are making are saving lives. My biggest worry is that in the quiet before the storm we forget how important our choices are and how many lives we are impacting.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Remember we talked about Chicken Little -- the moves we're making now almost feels like you're waiting b/c there is nothing you can see. But you have to make these moves early.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: Regarding the updated #StayHomeOhio order: We know that this social distancing is really making a difference. A quote from @nytimes: It spread quickly but it makes itself known slowly.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We want you to know that this is impacting young. Young people are being hospitalized. No deaths of those under 40 in #Ohio yet, but young people have died elsewhere. pic.twitter.com/LggQZ8zVM4

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted - Enforcement is a fundamental fairness issue. For the few who aren't following the order, we owe it to those who are following the rules to enforce the orders.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The action we're taking today is action that I know will save lives. We look forward to the day we can be back open and enjoy our lives and go see our friends and families again. #InThisTogetherOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Our @OhioStateParks are open, we don't want to close the state parks, but the @ohiodnr director can take action to enforce the orders we've issued.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Fishing: Fishing can continue, but people should observe proper social distancing not congregate together.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Campgrounds:  We are clarifying the stay at home order to close campgrounds with the exception where a camper or recreational vehicle in a campground serves as somebody’s permanent residence and they are unable to secure safe alternative housing.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Weddings: We are not going to regulate weddings. We leave it up to people's judgement. We've heard that some are having the full reception. The reception MUST follow the same rules -- no more than 10 people. Weddings are not exempt from this.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: People Traveling to Ohio: We ask those coming into our state to self-quarantined for 14 days. There are exemptions for those who work over state lines, but this is for those who have been out of state for some time.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: These businesses must ensure that people waiting to enter the stores must maintain safe social distancing.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We want people to be able to buy groceries, etc. but we also need for them to be safe.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Overcrowded stores: The new order requires retail businesses to establish the number of people who should be in the business at one time. We're not telling them the number b/c businesses are all different. But businesses must determine their number and post it.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Dispute resolution: We will appoint a board to evaluate and render guidance in situations where two local health departments have come to a different conclusion on what is or is not essential business.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The new order goes into effect when the previous order expires.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: If we are able to let up, we certainly can do that. The order is very similar to the previous order, but there are a few changes. The changes have come about b/c of what we've heard from the public.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are going to continue to see the numbers go up no matter what we do, but we can do all we can to keep the numbers down. Today I have asked Dr. Acton to extend the Department of Health’s Stay at Home Order to 11:59pm on May 1st.  This is extension is necessary. pic.twitter.com/H4IspOHYrt

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We've all seen the horror stories coming out of NY, out of Italy. What you are doing is buying time for our healthcare system to get the equipment it needs to build hospital space and do the things necessary so that the hospitals are not overrun.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We cannot let what we've accomplished go - we've accomplished a lot. We don't know when we will hit the peak. Between April 15 - May 15. It changes based on the info we have.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I want to talk directly to all Ohioans. Thank you for all you've been doing. The sacrifices you've been making. This isn't easy. We fully understand that. But we have to stay in this.

tweet: For those stores that do not have a mobile point of sale device, a SNAP recipient can continue to order online, then pick up the groceries/pay inside the grocery store. This option reduces the time SNAP recipients are in the grocery store and reduces the risk of community spread.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: With this change, the mom who does not have child care, the adult with an underlying health condition, or the senior citizen at high risk can order groceries at home and just go to the store to pay and pick up curbside, where available.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Now, those receiving SNAP benefits are able to shop online and go to their grocery stores to pick up their items in the cars. SNAP recipients will be able to swipe their EBT cards from their cars now without entering the store.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: To help ensure our most vulnerable Ohioans have access to food while helping to keep potential exposure to COVID-19 to a minimum, we have been working with our federal partners, the @USDANutrition, and the grocery stores on a “click and collect” option to get groceries.

tweet: We plan on utilizing freestanding emergency departments, urgent care centers, free-standing ambulatory surgery centers (not in use due to postponement of elective surgeries), and hospital multi-use healthcare facilities that house a lab service.

tweet: The second part of the order: We will start using rapid testing as soon as we get this in #Ohio. We think it will happen in the next week. We're looking forward to this.

tweet: There may be other hospitals that have the capacity and can do testing - when we confirm that we'll let you know.

tweet: Our @OHdeptofhealth  will continue to analyze tests for the most critical patients, including hospitalized and symptomatic healthcare workers.

tweet: They are much faster than the private labs. The turnaround at private labs is unacceptable for the patient and the rest of us.

tweet: I’ve asked Dr. Acton to require non-testing hospitals -- those that send their specimens to a third party to be tested -- to contract with any of the following labs: @OhioState, @MetroHealthCLE, @ClevelandClinic, @UHHospitals. These hospitals have the capacity to do tests.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We know #Ohio hasn't had as much testing as we would have liked. We had to ration the testing.

tweet: Prisons: There is no change in how I feel. I stated yesterday that people who run our prisons feel very strongly about their obligation to protect those working there and the prisoners. That is an obligation many probably don't realize. @OhioDRC has an aggressive protocol.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We want to get kids back to school, we want to open restaurants, open bars -- but we just can't do it yet. Again, this is once in 102 years, we have to do this and we have to stay at it. #InThisTogetherOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We've made difficult decisions, but we have to get through this. We can't let this monster come up - we have to keep pushing it down. This is a critical time. We haven't had anything like this for 102 years, so it has to be that type of response. pic.twitter.com/AODvq5mZoV

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This isn't time for browsing at the store. The work you are doing to physically distance yourself from others is absolutely life-saving.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I'm asking you to think as much as you can about essential activities. Every trip to the store. Every time you go get medicine, you want to minimize even that. You can do this. We need you to do this. It is so important that we minimize our exposure to others.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: It's really important to understand we have empty beds now, but it is the calm before the storm. We are working to double the capacity now. pic.twitter.com/LNR5q3nipn

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are working to get ready for this storm. We are not yellow. We have moved to blue stage, but there are some differences in models. I feel like the modelers at @OhioState are giving us the most realistic models. pic.twitter.com/XpAGbBuys2

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: What we are doing now will get us out of this faster and back to work faster.  I feel confident that we are using the best modeling possible. All models agree that #SocialDistancing is essential. pic.twitter.com/ttFrvMGDqs

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I feel like #Ohio made the decisive moves at the right time. We had to make hard decisions, but the moves to do #SocialDistancing is important. And now we are working to maximize the hospital capacity, but we still rely on physical distancing. pic.twitter.com/sE38xjaDKS

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: @DrAmyActon: Harvard Business Review Study: It focuses on Italy. Look at 2 regions: They could see a difference in the responses between these regions. pic.twitter.com/tkIxiUGeyk

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have tested 29,191 individuals in #Ohio. pic.twitter.com/2xaKcOk53D

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are still saving our testing for the most at risk. Most people are staying at home, and we can't know all those numbers, but we know that it is a significant amount.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: Today's #COVID19 dashboard: pic.twitter.com/p1wosueJkY

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: I had a call with nursing home operators, talking with them about their anxiety on the frontlines. For all of you in healthcare, we truly appreciate from the bottom of our hearts the sacrifices you are making for others. You are lifesavers, you are an inspiration.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: For employers and employees: A grace period was enacted on March 20 for employers that can't pay their premiums. There was also an order for out-of-network care. Insurers must provide the same rates that they would in-network. They are also required to pay for #COVID19 testing.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: So, for all of you who have had challenges with the unemployment systems, your voices are being heard and they're being acted on. Even if you have trouble, your benefits will be backdated to the date that you became eligible.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I was assured that they are putting 180 new people in the call center - they must first be trained. Also, @OhioBWC will train and lend some of their employees to this effort.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I wanted to convey to them that people are scared about the health/economic environment, and I wanted to bring an added sense of urgency. I was assured system capacity was increased 20x. They've added 100 staff to call center, but I said that isn't enough. We have to do more.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LTGovHusted: Unemployment compensation system: I was clear to those running this system, that many in the public were frustrated with having problems getting to the system. pic.twitter.com/jFXA1RsUKQ

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OhioMHAS: Remember that you are not alone. We're all #InThisTogetherOhio.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OhioMHAS: If you are feeling helpless or hopeless, please call the suicide prevention lifeline: 1-800-273-8255.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OhioMHAS: We are hearing about people having a hard time staying connected to their recovery supports. That connection is a lifeline for many people. For our friends in recovery, these are hard times. It is vitally important that you stay connected to your recovery support.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OhioMHAS: School is the community for the young people in our lives -- developmentally, friends are a primary importance to kids, especially teenagers. Please create opportunities for your kids to connect with classmates in new ways.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Living with purpose also contributes to our sense of wellness. If you are working/studying from home, you might be at a pace where you're not having physically-distanced social opportunities -- so build that in.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OhioMHAS: If you are involved in a faith community, stay connected to your faith leaders. Connect online or on social media. You can go to  http://coronavirus.ohio.gov  to learn more about resources for faith communities. pic.twitter.com/VYwd9sw58d

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OhioMHAS: Checking on neighbors and friends who live alone is very important right now. Call them and talk, help decrease the isolation.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
.@OhioMHAS: For some of us, we are spending a lot of time with our families - maybe too much time. That can be stressful. Or, if you live alone, you may be lonely. 

Tips: Wake up at the same time, shower, get dressed, have meals at normal times. Schedule leisure time too.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OhioMHAS Director: Home has taken on a new meaning for all of us now. We know not everyone has a safe place to live, but we are working with partners to make sure every Ohio family, youth, or adult experiencing homelessness has a place to live. pic.twitter.com/X0djw0gAnd

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: One thing we worry about is our citizen's mental health during this challenging time. Mental health concerns all of us. Keeping your mental health strong is very important.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This is another reason why we need to slow down the spread. We need to buy time to allow this technology like this to come online. It will make a huge difference.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are so very, very grateful for their hard work and know that with this more rapid diagnostic process, health care providers and public health officials can better identify, treat, and prevent the spread of COVID-19.  This work will save lives.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@OSUWexMed will administer the new test under its existing FDA certification permits.  Since March 14th, 100 researchers and clinicians have worked with Battelle researchers at night and on the weekends to stand up the lab that will support COVID-19 testing.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Right now, the system can process approximately 200 tests per day, but when the infrastructure is fully built up over the coming days, the goal is to process more than 1,000 test swabs per day.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@Battelle and @OSUWexMed have jointly developed a new rapid, sensitive diagnostic COVID-19 test.  The new rapid test will allow for fast turnaround time on test results, which will help #FlattenTheCurve.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: There will also be guidance to help minimize water quality degradation related to deteriorated, stagnant water in plumbing that can lead to health risks.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: When a homeowner gets their water turned back on after a period of it being inactive, they must first flush the system.  The Ohio EPA will be putting out guidance on how to do this, and we will get it up on  http://coronavirus.ohio.gov .

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: For those who are eligible to get their water reinstated, they must call their water utility to request the reinstatement. The reconnection will happen without any fees.  However, it doesn’t excuse people from paying the bill, you will still need to pay your bill moving forward

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: 2. If someone previously had their water shut off dating back to January 1st, the water system is required to reconnect. This will help us assure that as many people as possible have safe water during the state of emergency.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
This order does two things: 

1. It prevents a water system from shutting off someone’s water service due to non-payment during the declared state of emergency;

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Our @OhioEPA director just signed a statewide order a few moments ago to maintain public water service during the #COVID19 state of emergency.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I’ve also asked them to find additional remote work opportunities.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
This is so important to help us keep social distancing. 
As Dr. Acton and I have said again and again, social distancing must continue to protect all Ohioans. I have directed state agencies to continue with current teleworking arrangements through at least Friday, May 1, 2020.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: On March 12th, I directed state agencies to begin assigning state employees to telework.  Since that time, we’ve successfully deployed a large number of state employees -- almost 18,000 -- to do their work remotely.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Inventory is to be reported online at  http://coronavirus.ohio.gov/VentInventory  each Wednesday by 5:00pm, with the first report due tomorrow. Hospitals also are to continue to report daily ventilator data through the Ohio Hospital Association reporting tool.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
Exemptions include:
➡️Ventilators in the possession of individuals for personal use; and
➡️Ventilators that are in transit across Ohio but are being delivered from and to other states.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Along with mechanical ventilators, other devices to be reported are C-PAP and B-PAP machines commonly used to treat sleep apnea, as well as anesthetic machines and various treatment masks and tubing.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: It also will help our regional hospital collaboratives by giving them information on the availability of these machines in their regions.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This will allow for the identification and re-distribution of machines from healthcare providers who are no longer performing elective procedures.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The order requires weekly on-line reporting of these devices by any entity in the supply chain, from creation through end use. Examples are manufacturers, producers, wholesalers, transporters, distributors, retailers, physicians, clinics, hospitals, and medical facilities.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Ventilators: Today @DrAmyActon is issuing an order to help us keep track of where the ventilators are, how many we have -- so if there is a shortage and we have to move them around, we'll be able to do that.  we're also working independently to secure more ventilators.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The lending support is intended to sustain small Southeast Ohio businesses during this #COVID19 outbreak and create sustainable growth for the Region beyond the crisis.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This partnership comes at a critical time when Appalachian Growth Capital is working to help more small companies in Appalachian Ohio with financing during this economically difficult time.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The JobsOhio investment is a long-term, low interest loan that will boost AGC’s ability to provide low interest funding to businesses in the Appalachian community.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: AGC provides small business financing in the 32-Appalachian Counties of eastern and southern Ohio.  It works with local and regional banks, as well as secondary lenders to support businesses in the region.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Today, @JobsOhio is announcing that it is providing a $2 million growth fund loan to Appalachian Growth Capital, or AGC.  This announcement is part of JobsOhio’s new strategic initiative to provide more economic development funds to areas of #Ohio hardest hit by the economy.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: One of the great assets we have in #Ohio is @JobsOhio - I've asked them to think about how they can be value-added when this is over. I've asked the board to think of ways they can help our economy.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Reminder: At essential stores, it's an obligation of the store, as well as the customers to keep the social distancing. It's also the responsibility of the store manager to make sure the store is safe, and that it keeps separate, distinct hours for our vulnerable populations.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: In regard to the physical distancing. We have to keep this up. Most people are doing great - it's buying our medical community additional time to get ready. It makes a difference. pic.twitter.com/A3uizkxus6

tweet: .@LtGovHusted: Every day we have the opportunity to be part of the solution or part of the problem. We know that not everyone is getting the message about #SocialDistancing -- those who do get it, we need your help to pass the information on to others.

tweet: It is a concern as the weather gets better. How well we do is determined by each individual in #Ohio and how well they stay away from others.

tweet: If you look at the weather yesterday, it was a great day to be out. But as the weather gets better, you are seeing people congregate in Metroparks and different places.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The CDC guidelines and information about all of these funding opportunities are on the  http://coronavirus.ohio.gov  website. The site will continue to be updated as this work progresses.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This Department is also deploying some federal funds to cover additional expenses that Adult Care Facilities are taking on because of COVID19.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Further, our @OhioMhas is directing some federal opioid response funding to help people living in recovery housing or engaged in treatment to maintain their current housing and prevent homelessness.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are asking all local communities to include homeless shelters in your planning so that we can more quickly help support these Ohioans to meet the social distancing guidelines.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: A big challenge is still helping reduce the number of people in homeless shelters.  Shelters aren’t built for social distancing, so many communities are finding alternates to shelter or spreading out to other locations.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: For example, the CDC issued guidelines about homeless shelters and domestic violence shelters. While these documents are available to communities in Ohio now, our state Homelessness Team is customizing those for Ohio’s local use.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Homeless: Every day we talk about #SocialDistancing, but there are some people who rely on homeless shelters. We've created a Homelessness Team dedicated to this specific issue.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: They are also gearing up to make face shields.  They are currently sourcing out the materials and making patterns.  Further, each prison that has its own workshop will make masks for the people in those prisons.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: They are awaiting the delivery ingredients around April14th, and should be able to make 1,460 gallons of hand sanitizer.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: They will be able to start making cough masks – similar to surgical masks -- soon and will be able to make 5,000 a day up to a total of 2 million.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Prisons: Our @DRCOhio prisons are working to make #PPE. So far inmates have made 500 hospital gowns. They will be able to make 44,000 when they get additional fabric.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: K-12: Our original order to close school buildings was for 3 weeks. We're giving an additional order that will take this to May 1, which is a Friday. We will reevaluate as we get closer to that date. pic.twitter.com/OyFNtSK8Lu

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We must slow this virus down. It's a race for time as we build out the hospital capacity. It also buys us time for new technology to come online and help us in a number of ways. Every day that we can delay this tidal wave is a day we can see technology move forward.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The @OHdeptofhealth can get test results back within a matter of hours. The private labs do good work, but they are behind --- ODH is not.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: To all the hospitals, we request that you please send your samples to a neighboring hospital that does quick testing or send it to @OHdeptofhealth. I don't think it is acceptable while we are in this crisis to wait 5-6 days - this is what we're seeing in the outside, private labs

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted believe it is very important that we have a group of businessmen and women that reflect #Ohio to give us advice on who we move forward on the economic front. We are assembling this group now.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The @US_FDA authorization will allow @Battelle to sterilize masks without a daily limit. The Battelle Critical Care Decontamination System is capable of decontaminating up to 80,000 respirator masks per system each day. This will save lives! #InThisTogetherOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This will not only help #Ohio's healthcare workers on the front lines of the #COVID19 crisis but @Battelle will also be helping health care workers in hot spots throughout the country including New York and Washington state.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet:
Thank you @realDonaldTrump and @SteveFDA! 
@US_FDA has now given Columbus-based @Battelle full approval of the use of new technology to sterilize desperately-needed N95 masks in #Ohio and other parts of the United States.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted and I just had a very productive call w/ @US_FDA about expanding @Battelle’s authorization to sterilize N95 masks in #Ohio & elsewhere in the US. I anticipate a positive announcement soon. We must do all we can to protect our frontline workers. #InThisTogetherOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I talked with @NYGovCuomo a short time ago to update him on @Battelle's sterilization technology and our progress with @US_FDA. He was happy to hear that this critical N95 sterilization could soon be happening for frontline workers in NY. We'll update everyone when we hear more.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Thank you, Mr. President, for your attention to this urgent matter. https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1244296475254968320 …

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I wanted to close by sharing a performance that was specifically shared with our office by Malone University’s Chorale. Thank you, Dr. Peterson and the Malone University Virtual Choir. To all of #Ohio: May the Lord Bless You and Keep You. #InThisTogetherOhio https://twitter.com/MaloneU/status/1244334511074299904 …

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The urgency of today is b/c we know that we have people on the frontline today who don't' have the masks they need. They are using masks longer than they normally would, but they are doing it because they don't have a choice.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We do what we have to do to protect Ohioans. What happened today is we've compressed into a short period of time what sometimes takes days. We hope this will allow us to get the approval for @Battelle before midnight tonight so that they can help us save people.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The second lesson is that we never want to be in a position where we can't buy very important medical equipment in this country. We have to source this equipment in this country.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I think when we come out of this, one of the lessons we are learning as a country is that we have to invest more public health. It's not a Democrat problem, it's not a Republican problem.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I called the @realDonaldTrump this morning. The President called me back. I explained to him what is happening. We had a good conversation. He understands that we want to protect our first responders/hospital employees. He was great. He said "I'm moving. I'll get this done."

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@Battelle: We plan to take masks from all over the state. We are ready to help everyone. #InThisTogetherOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I expect a decision today. I'm an impatient guy, but lives are literally at stake. We want everyone in the country to understand the importance of this. It's why I called the President. The @US_FDA commissioner assured me this would be done today. I'm cautiously optimistic.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@Battelle's Lew Von Thaer: We've proven this technology and we've built a system that can clean and reuse masks up to 20 times. pic.twitter.com/qEagN6cnqp

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: The sterilization was only allowed to occur on a limited basis - and that's just not good enough. Your Governor, Lt. Governor - our entire team is fighting for #PPE.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: We want everyone to know that we've been pushing this for a week. We've been waiting patiently. We were told on Wednesday that they would have a solution by the end of the week, and when I got the call at 1:19 am I was thrilled, but the devil was in the details.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: A few minutes ago I talked with the @US_FDA  commissioner who tells us this will be cleared up today. We're not there yet, but I'm hopeful.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: This won't solve every single problem, but it is going to help here in #Ohio and across this country. I'm again making the appeal to @US_FDA that we need this technology at full capacity.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: I spoke with @realDonaldTrump and he told me he would do everything he could to get full approval today so that these machines can be fully operational.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: But we quickly learned that it was only partial approval.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@Battelle is ready to go forward, but we've been waiting for @US_FDA approval. @LtGovHusted has been working on this. We've been waiting and waiting...and waiting. A little after 1am we got what we thought was good news - that they'd approved it and we could start moving forward

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: One is ready to be sent to Seattle, and one to the Washington, D.C./Maryland/Virginia area.  They have the ability in the next few weeks to make 15 more machines and send them to different parts of the country.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: They now have now developed machines with the capability to sterilize 80,000 used surgical masks a day.  We have two of these machines in Ohio.  One is in New York, with another on the way.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@Battelle is the largest, private, non-profit research and development organization in the world.  Battelle’s historical inventions have included contributions to the Xerox copy machine, cruise control, the compact disc, and bar codes.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Innovation is in Ohio’s DNA.  And we need the help of Ohio’s scientists, engineers, and researchers now more than ever.  @Battelle opened its doors in 1929 in Columbus with a mission to help solve the world’s most pressing issues using groundbreaking science and technology.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are working very, very hard to find these masks. This is a problem that is not unique to #Ohio. It's a problem all over the country. We're working every day - but we also have something that can help us: that's the amazing work done by @Battelle.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: All air goes through the mask so you’re not breathing in germs and not breathing out germs.  These masks are so very important for our medical personnel and our first responders. These individuals charge toward danger when the rest of us pull back. They need this help.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have a huge problem as we look at the surge coming at us. We do not have enough N95 masks. They’re usually round and are actually fitted to the face to work to make sure air doesn’t leak out around the bridge of your nose and under your chin. pic.twitter.com/zfIop4SYrr

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We made the decision when we did the order not to infringe on religious liberty, but this is a critical time -- for the safety of everyone, I can't imagine that there is anyone who would want to take that risk.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: That number is not our destiny, we impact it with our behavior - with our #SocialDistancing.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We are lengthening the onset of the peak time and flattening the curve. The flattening is happening in #Ohio, but how much we flatten will depend on all of us.  #InThisTogetherOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: It's complicated, but you don't have to trust the modeling to see what's happening in other states. We are planning for worst-case scenarios with the hope that everything we do will take us away from that number.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: The numbers are a range. I know 8,000-10,000 sounds like a lot, but that really isn't a huge amount of Ohioans.  We want it to spread slower, but it is spreading. When we stay home, the effectiveness will show up in our data a few weeks from now.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We had a conversation with mayors this morning. Different health departments are going out and closing businesses that are not essential. You can expect that to continue. Today I asked all the chiefs of police to give us a report of what they are seeing as far as compliance. pic.twitter.com/Q3mUMNT6YN

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: At least two of our hospitals have figured out how to put more than one person on a ventilator. Innovation is happening in #Ohio.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: There is a real sense of urgency in #Ohio. The @OHNationalGuard will be helping hospitals where they can. The whole goal is to increase capacity as soon as possible. Our team is working every day to try to obtain more ventilators.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: I've heard horrifying stories of people without insurance being turned away across the country. We don't want hospitals to turn anyone away in #Ohio.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: Keep your chin up, we're fighting through this. We're going to get through this. By our actions, we can all be part of the solution. #InThisTogetherOhio

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: Businesses: Even when we start to phase out of this in the future, we are still going to have to practice safe workplace practices. You have to make sure the message is getting through all the way to your employees.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: #Ohio has opted in. We are working on getting the system up and running.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: The federal package signed by President Trump: States had to opt into the provisions -- which includes 1099 and self-employed individuals.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: We have more information on how @PBS is going to help supplement education on our website:  http://coronavirus.ohio.gov/learnathome  pic.twitter.com/rT9znMOX9y

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@LtGovHusted: We know a lot of students don't have access to the internet, and even if you have it might be slow b/c of the current demand. Now, @PBS stations will be offering educational television for kids to tune into. pic.twitter.com/BNOk8MsMOj

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: For those of you who know me, I'd rather be out digging in the dirt. We want you to go outside, get out there in nature -- at a social distance. Enjoy the beautiful weather and help those most vulnerable. pic.twitter.com/6GSo9pk9kA

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: I want you to think about the elderly in our neighborhoods. #Ohio, like Italy, skews toward an elderly population. They are extremely vulnerable. We can still grocery shop - but I'd rather the elderly not go out at all. Please help your neighbors. #InThisTogether

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: What we know is this - There is no scenario without a hurricane, we are in the blue curve. What you are doing is helping us. What is important is that every day we don't spread #COVID19 makes all the difference for our frontline healthcare workers. pic.twitter.com/CiJW8SUeol

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: Even though the 8,000 - 10,000 cases a day number seems high, we are flattening the curve. These numbers would have been much, much higher had we not taken action when we did. The actions you are taking at home are shrinking those numbers.

name: Governor Mike DeWine
tweet: .@DrAmyActon: Picture a hurricane in its early stages. First, they tell us where it might land, but they can't say when or where exactly it will hit. Then as you get closer, your predications get better. Similarly, our models are giving us a compass. pic.twitter.com/qwwoJaaYHQ
